AB  - Using data for nearly 100 countries, cross-country inequality indexes for five major ‘basic needs’ indicators are computed and compared with income inequality indexes. Except for physician supply, inter-country inequality in meeting basic needs appears much smaller than income inequality. While inter-country income disparity increased, inequality in basic needs indicators declined during 1960–1978.
